  "response_text": "# Running in High-Pollution Cities\n\n## Best Outdoor Times\n- **Early morning (5-7 AM)**: Pollution typically lowest before traffic peaks\n- **After rain**: Air clears noticeably for a few hours\n- **Weekends/holidays**: Reduced vehicle emissions\n- Check real-time AQI apps (AirVisual, IQAir) before heading out\n\n## Location Priorities (If Going Outside)\n- Parks with tree coverage (trees filter some particles)\n- Waterfront areas where breezes help disperse pollution\n- Elevated spots away from street-level exhaust\n- Away from major roads and industrial zones\n\n## Indoor Alternatives (More Realistic Long-Term)\n- **Gym treadmills** with air filtration\n- **Shopping malls** (climate-controlled, some allow early morning walking)\n- **Indoor tracks** at sports facilities\n- **Stair climbing** in your building\n- **Home workouts** (YouTube routines, jump rope)\n- **Swimming pools** (excellent full-body alternative)\n\n## Honest Assessment\nIn severe pollution conditions (AQI >150), outdoor running genuinely risks respiratory damage. The health gains from running can be offset by pollution exposure. Many serious runners in these cities shift to:\n- Early morning when possible\n- Primarily indoor training\n- Relocating temporarily during worst seasons\n\nWhat's your current AQI range? That would help refine recommendations.",
